le in the workspace, and also check what sessions are active.\\n\\nCurrent time: 21:41 UTC, 14 Apr\\n\\nLet me analyze the current sessions:\\n\\n1. `cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — THIS session, running (my cron session)\\n2. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258` — running, but last updated 21:40:33 (just 8 minutes ago), child sessions ended normally\\n\\n\\n3. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134` — done, ended at 21:38:08, was a child session that finished\\n4. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` — running, last updated 21:37:54, child sessions showed completed work\\n5. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — running, last updated 21:40:57, was aborted but continues running\\n\\nNow I'm looking at the heartbeat system state to compare against. Looking at the last stable state around 21:40, I see the main cron job, the QLHV monitor, and the DTLX monitor all running, with the QLHV group session and the agent status cron both showing activity. The direct message session appears to have ended.\\n\\nComparing that snapshot to right now, there's no meaningful change—the same five sessions are still running with the same statuses, and the direct message that ended was just a child session that completed normally rather than a parent cron job. There's a minor timestamp difference but nothing that warrants alerting.\\n\\nI'm realizing the heartbeat state file might not exist or the memory system isn't finding it, which is why the DTLX monitor session is still running. Looking at the telegram group messages more carefully, the most recent status from 21:37 shows the cron jobs and group session running, and nothing has changed since then. Since my job is specifically the DTLX 5p monitor and there are no actual changes to report, I should stay silent and exit quietly.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"S